{0 Development}

{1 Testing}

{2 Principles}

{ol
    {- {b Sexp over helpers.}
       Test helpers make test failure hard to debug.
       Prefer [@@deriving sexp] on types and print with [Sexp.to_string_hum]
       rather than writing custom [pp_*] pretty-printers.
       {b Exception:} [Ascii_table] helpers are encouraged for tabular test cases
       where side-by-side comparison aids review.}

    {- {b Spec ↔ test cross-referencing.}
       We like bidirectional map between specification and tests.}

    {- {b Property-based testing (PBT).}
       Use Jane Street [Quickcheck] (via [ppx_quick_test]) for invariant-heavy code.
       Good candidates:
       {ul
           {- Roundtrip properties, e.g. [make (content_of (to_commonmark wl)) = wl]
              (see {!Parse.Wikilink}).}
           {- Resolution idempotence: resolving an already-resolved vault is a no-op.}
           {- Slug uniqueness within a document.}
           {- Embed expansion always terminates within [max_depth].}
       }
       Write focused generators that avoid delimiter characters ([#], [|], [\[\[]], [\]\] ])
       so that generated values stay in the canonical domain of the function under test.
       See {!Parse.Wikilink} for an example.}

    {- {b Trace-based testing.}
       Where feasible, instrument functions with [trace] to capture intermediate
       states (e.g. resolution candidates considered, embed recursion path).
       This lets tests assert on {e internal} correctness, not just input/output.}
}
